    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv. For each file, output the following compact aggregates only: 1) total number of rows; 2) minimum and maximum timestamp; 3) list of unique cmdb_id values with their row counts (limit to top 50 by count); 4) list of unique KPI/trace/log names (for metric use kpi_name, for trace use trace_name, for log use log_name) with their row counts (limit to top 50). Do not print raw time series rows. Return results in a structured format (one block per file)."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous aggregate scan: metric.csv contains many KPI series (321,454 rows) spanning 2022-03-21 01:30 to 02:30 (UTC+8) across ~59 cmdb_id components and ~1,384 KPI names; trace.csv and log.csv cover the incident window (02:00–02:29 UTC+8) and list many per-service traces and two log metrics (log.error_count, log.row_count). error_logs.csv is empty. We should next narrow candidates via metric anomaly detection within the incident window. According to the rules, global thresholds must be calculated using the full available series for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) before filtering to the incident window. Then we should count anomalies in the incident window (points >= global P95 or <= global P5) to rank the most anomalous component-KPIs and get earliest anomaly times to drive further trace/log inspection.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For metric.csv only, do the following (use all rows to compute thresholds before filtering):\n1) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) group, compute the global P95 and global P5 of the 'value' using the entire metric.csv series.\n2) Then filter metric.csv to rows within the incident window: March 21, 2022 02:00:00 to 02:30:00 (UTC+8).\n3) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) in that window, compute: total_points_in_window, anomaly_count_high = count(value >= global_P95), anomaly_count_low = count(value <= global_P5), earliest_anomaly_ts (earliest timestamp in the window where value >= P95 or <= P5), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, global_P95, global_P5.\n4) Return the top 20 groups ranked by (anomaly_count_high + anomaly_count_low) in descending order. For ties, rank by earliest_anomaly_ts ascending. Limit output columns to: cmdb_id, kpi_name, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count_high, anomaly_count_low, earliest_anomaly_ts, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, global_P95, global_P5. Do not print raw time series. Keep results compact."
}

{
    "analysis": "The previous step computed per-(cmdb_id, kpi_name) global P95/P5 thresholds and anomaly counts restricted to the incident window. The top 20 groups were dominated by adservice KPIs that show no variance across their full series (global_P95 == global_P5 and max == min). Those constant-series KPIs produce misleading anomaly counts (every point meets both >=P95 and <=P5). We should ignore constant KPI series and re-rank candidate component-KPIs by real anomalies (non-constant series) to find meaningful faults. After that, we will narrow to the most anomalous components/times and use trace.csv and log.csv to localize root causes for the two failures.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Repeat the metric group anomaly ranking but exclude KPI series that are constant. Specifically: using the full metric.csv to compute global_P95 and global_P5 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name), identify and exclude groups where global_P95 == global_P5 or where the group's global max == global min. Then, filter to the incident window (2022-03-21 02:00:00 to 02:30:00 UTC+8) and for each remaining (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute: total_points_in_window, anomaly_count_high (value >= global_P95), anomaly_count_low (value <= global_P5), earliest_anomaly_ts (first timestamp in window where value breaches), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, global_P95, global_P5. Return the top 20 groups ranked by (anomaly_count_high + anomaly_count_low) desc, tiebreaker earliest_anomaly_ts asc. Limit output columns to: cmdb_id, kpi_name, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count_high, anomaly_count_low, earliest_anomaly_ts, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, global_P95, global_P5. Keep results compact."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous steps: I scanned all telemetry files and computed per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) global thresholds and anomaly counts within the incident window. The metric analysis returned many constant-series metrics (mostly adservice) where global_P95 == global_P5 and max==min, producing misleading anomaly counts. After excluding constant series, there were no metric anomalies left in the incident window. Therefore metrics alone did not reveal non-constant faults during the two failures. Next I should analyze traces (and then logs) within the incident window since traces often reveal service-level errors (error_rate, duration spikes, row_count drops) and can localize the two failures in time and component. I will request a compact ranked list of trace groups showing real anomalies based on global thresholds computed on the full trace series (not filtered).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For trace.csv only: 1) Using the full trace.csv, compute global P95 and global P5 of 'value' for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) group. 2) Filter trace.csv to the incident window March 21, 2022 02:00:00 to 02:30:00 (UTC+8). 3) For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) in that window compute: total_points_in_window, anomaly_count_high = count(value >= global_P95), anomaly_count_low = count(value <= global_P5), earliest_anomaly_ts (earliest timestamp in window where value breaches), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, global_P95, global_P5. 4) Exclude groups that are constant across their full series (global_P95 == global_P5 or global max == global min). 5) Return the top 20 groups ranked by (anomaly_count_high + anomaly_count_low) descending, tiebreaker earliest_anomaly_ts ascending. Limit output columns to: cmdb_id, trace_name, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count_high, anomaly_count_low, earliest_anomaly_ts, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, global_P95, global_P5. Keep results compact and do not return raw time series."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have scanned metrics and found no non-constant metric anomalies in the incident window; many metric KPIs were constant and thus uninformative. Trace analysis (non-constant groups) did reveal many anomalies starting at 2022-03-21 02:00:00 UTC+8 across multiple services (row_count and duration traces). This implies trace-level disruptions at or near 02:00, but we still need to (1) determine whether there are two separate failure events inside 02:00–02:30 and their exact occurrence times, and (2) identify the root cause component and reason for each event. To locate distinct failures we should find time points (minute resolution) where many trace groups simultaneously breach their global thresholds (high or low). Those peak timestamps will give candidate occurrence times for the failures and the list of affected services at those times will help localize the root cause. After we identify the two peak timestamps, we'll inspect trace types (row_count vs duration) and then use log.csv (log.error_count and log.row_count) for the candidate components at those times to determine if the root cause is a service/pod or a resource-level issue.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv and the global thresholds computed from the full trace series (exclude constant groups where global_P95 == global_P5 or global max == min), do the following within the incident window March 21, 2022 02:00:00 to 02:30:00 (UTC+8):\n1) For each timestamp (minute) in the window, count the number of trace-group anomalies where value >= global_P95 OR value <= global_P5. Produce the top 10 timestamps ranked by anomaly count (desc). For each top timestamp return: timestamp, anomaly_count_total.\n2) For the top 2 timestamps from step 1, provide for each timestamp a compact breakdown: (a) top 10 affected cmdb_id by number of anomalous trace groups at that timestamp (cmdb_id, anomalous_group_count); (b) counts of anomalous trace types at that timestamp: number of row_count-type traces anomalous, number of duration_p95/duration_mean-type traces anomalous, number of error_rate-type traces anomalous; (c) list up to 20 (cmdb_id, trace_name, breach_type) rows that were anomalous at that timestamp where breach_type is 'high' or 'low'.\nLimit outputs to the requested compact aggregates and lists; do not print raw time series. Keep results structured and concise."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have exhausted metric signals (most were constant and non-informative). Trace analysis shows clear multi-service anomalies concentrated at specific minutes; the highest anomaly-count minutes are 2022-03-21 02:29:00 and 2022-03-21 02:09:00 (UTC+8), and many trace groups (row_count and duration traces) breach their historical thresholds at those minutes. To localize root cause components for the two failures we must (a) determine which services are the most downstream faulty components at each peak minute using trace directionality (trace.from_*, trace.to_*, trace.self.*), and (b) corroborate with logs (log.error_count and log.row_count) at those minutes to identify the reason (e.g., high latency, request drops, or errors). Next, we should produce compact per-service directional anomaly counts and a sample of anomalous trace rows at each of the two peak timestamps to identify downstream faulty services and candidate root causes. This will let us pick the likely root-cause component and exact minute per failure to confirm with logs.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For trace.csv only, focus on timestamps 2022-03-21 02:29:00 and 2022-03-21 02:09:00 (UTC+8). Using the global thresholds computed from the full trace series (exclude constant groups where global_P95 == global_P5 or global max == min), do the following for each of the two timestamps independently:\n1) Produce a ranked list (top 20) of cmdb_id by number of anomalous trace groups at that timestamp. For each cmdb_id include: cmdb_id, anomalous_group_count, to_count (number of anomalous trace_name containing 'trace.to_'), from_count (containing 'trace.from_'), self_count (containing 'trace.self').\n2) Return up to 20 anomalous trace rows at that timestamp (limit 20) with these columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, breach_type ('high' if value >= global_P95 else 'low' if value <= global_P5), value, global_P95, global_P5.\nKeep outputs compact and structured; do not print full time series. Use the full trace.csv to compute thresholds before filtering to these timestamps."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have exhausted metric signals (most metric KPIs were constant and uninformative) and found strong trace-level anomalies concentrated at specific minutes. The highest anomaly-count minutes are 2022-03-21 02:29:00 and 2022-03-21 02:09:00 (UTC+8). At those minutes many services show anomalous 'to_' traces (outgoing calls) and many backend services show anomalous 'from_' traces (incoming calls). By the localization rules, the root cause is typically the most downstream faulty service in the call chain — i.e., components with anomalous 'from_' (receiving) or 'self' traces at the peak minutes are prime root-cause candidates. From the earlier breakdowns, productcatalogservice-* and cartservice-* and several checkoutservice/frontend variants appear frequently; productcatalogservice-2 and checkoutservice-* showed many 'from' or 'self' anomalies at top minutes. To decide the exact root-cause component and reason for each failure, we must (for each peak minute) (1) rank components by their downstream-facing anomaly counts (from_count + self_count) to pick the most downstream faulty candidates, and (2) corroborate with logs at that minute (log.error_count, log.row_count) to identify the underlying reason (e.g., errors, request drops). The next step is to produce per-timestamp downstream-focused candidate rankings and check their logs at those minutes.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For trace.csv and log.csv together, do the following (use full series to compute global thresholds for each group before filtering):\n1) For each of the two timestamps 2022-03-21 02:29:00 and 2022-03-21 02:09:00 (UTC+8), from trace.csv (exclude constant groups where global_P95 == global_P5 or global max == min) identify all anomalous trace rows at that single timestamp (value >= global_P95 OR value <= global_P5).\n2) For each timestamp, aggregate those anomalous trace rows by cmdb_id and compute: anomalous_group_count, from_count = number of anomalous trace_name containing 'trace.from_', self_count = number containing 'trace.self', to_count = number containing 'trace.to_'. Return the top 10 cmdb_id ranked by (from_count + self_count) descending; include the three counts and anomalous_group_count.\n3) For each cmdb_id in those top-10 lists (for both timestamps), fetch log.csv rows at that exact timestamp and cmdb_id (if present) for log_name in {log.error_count, log.row_count}. Using the full log.csv series, compute global P95 and P5 per (cmdb_id, log_name) first, and indicate for each fetched log row whether value >= global_P95 (mark 'high') or value <= global_P5 (mark 'low'), and include value, global_P95, global_P5. If no log row exists for a given (cmdb_id, timestamp), return an explicit 'missing' marker.\n4) Limit outputs: for each timestamp return (A) the top-10 downstream-focused cmdb_id table; (B) for those cmdb_ids, the log status rows (at most 20 rows per timestamp). Keep results compact and structured; do not print full series."
}

